<div id="review_3634658143" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3634658143" />
    <a title="Alistair Edwards" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/56886924-alistair-edwards"><img alt="Alistair Edwards" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3634658143?book_show_action=true">Nov 08, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Alistair Edwards" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Alistair Edwards" href="/user/show/56886924-alistair-edwards">Alistair Edwards</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780099328100" href="/book/show/1541910.The_Speaker_Of_Mandarin">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3634658143" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10145183513569128385"> Part 1 is unusual. Wexford is on holiday, in China. There is a death, but he is on holiday and does not get involved; it may have been an accident, anyway. So there is now detectiving in this part and I could not help wondering what the significance was of it was. One might think that it was just a chance for the author to show off her knowledge of Chinese culture and history, but then she is Ruth Rendell, who has no need to show off.<br/><br/>Of course the connection becomes apparent in Part 2. (No spoi</span>
  <span id="freeText10145183513569128385" style="display:none"> Part 1 is unusual. Wexford is on holiday, in China. There is a death, but he is on holiday and does not get involved; it may have been an accident, anyway. So there is now detectiving in this part and I could not help wondering what the significance was of it was. One might think that it was just a chance for the author to show off her knowledge of Chinese culture and history, but then she is Ruth Rendell, who has no need to show off.<br /><br />Of course the connection becomes apparent in Part 2. (No spoilers, so I won't explain too much).<br /><br />There are a lot of twists which are intriguing and entertaining. In the end the culprit comes (or it did to me) as quite a surprise. My only niggle would be that if Wexford had stuck to good old-fashinoned policing – instead of being distracted by a lot of Chinese intrigue – then he might have solved this one much more quickly. </span>
  <a data-text-id="10145183513569128385" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


