    <a title="Joyce" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7199574-joyce"><img alt="Joyce" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3440656528?book_show_action=true">Jul 14, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joyce" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joyce" href="/user/show/7199574-joyce">Joyce</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/19074235-speaker-of-mandarin">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3440656528" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11694242977595198883"><strong>Interesting Plot But Unsatisfactory Solution</strong><br/><br/>This is only the third Rendell book I’ve read but I see a pattern developing. The guilty party comes out of left field- generally no one you ever considered. While the plot lines are interesting, I find this a little off putting, almost anticlimactic. While I’m sure it’s meant to show how clever Wexford is, it’s never fully clear how to comes to the discovery of the guilty party. <br/><br/>There are so many characters to keep track of, most of whom are not prese</span>
  <span id="freeText11694242977595198883" style="display:none"><strong>Interesting Plot But Unsatisfactory Solution</strong><br /><br />This is only the third Rendell book I’ve read but I see a pattern developing. The guilty party comes out of left field- generally no one you ever considered. While the plot lines are interesting, I find this a little off putting, almost anticlimactic. While I’m sure it’s meant to show how clever Wexford is, it’s never fully clear how to comes to the discovery of the guilty party. <br /><br />There are so many characters to keep track of, most of whom are not presented in any depth and many unsavory. <br /><br />I’m not sure I’m a huge fan of the authors style. </span>
  <a data-text-id="11694242977595198883" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


